abstract: At a time when the album is dying, the “making of a classic album” book strategy seems to be a growth industry.
snippet: At a time when the album is dying, the “making of a classic album” book strategy seems to be a growth industry.
lead_paragraph: The album is dying. As a format of recorded music, the album — LP, CD, record, disc, platter, licorice pizza, whatever — has been tossed aside by file sharing and the iPod. Tower Records, rest in peace. For better or worse, pop music has effectively returned to the days before the Beatles arrived, when everything was strictly one single at a time.

abstract: The music critics of The New York Times offer previews of 23 of New York’s better New Year’s Eve shows  each of which promises its own mixture of indulgence, hilarity and hysteria.
snippet: The music critics of The New York Times offer previews of 23 of New York’s better New Year’s Eve shows  each of which promises its own mixture of indulgence, hilarity and hysteria.
lead_paragraph: THE last notes of 2006, the first song of 2007 — those are big symbolic responsibilities for musicians to take on and for listeners to seek out, but there’s no shortage of volunteers. Nightlife in New York City on New Year’s Eve has an edge of indulgence, hilarity and hysteria, and it’s premium-priced as a promise that performers will offer up not just a concert, but an occasion. Here are previews of 23 of the night’s better shows, chosen by music critics of The New York Times.

abstract: Ben Sisario recommends seeing Patti Smith at Bowery Ballroom on New Year's Eve; drawing (M)
snippet: Ben Sisario recommends seeing Patti Smith at Bowery Ballroom on New Year's Eve; drawing (M)
lead_paragraph: Every new year should start like a Patti Smith song: passionate, cleansing and in no particular hurry. And for the last nine years that's exactly how it has begun at the Bowery Ballroom, with Ms. Smith leading her band for a few nights in the rhapsodic and elemental music -- like "Gloria," which transforms a rock standard into an erotic psychodrama -- that brought her to prominence in the 1970s. It has been a big year for Ms. Smith. In October she presided over the last night at CBGB, the Bowery cave where she started, and shortly thereafter made her third appearance at the Metropolitan Museum of Art in a tribute to Joan of Arc. Tomorrow she hits another milestone: her 60th birthday. May she have many happy returns. At 9 p.m., 6 Delancey Street, near the Bowery, (212) 533-2111, boweryballroom.com; sold out.

abstract: Nate Chinen recommends seeing performance by Steven Bernstein's Millennial Territory Orchestra at Tonic on New Year's Eve; drawing (M)
snippet: Nate Chinen recommends seeing performance by Steven Bernstein's Millennial Territory Orchestra at Tonic on New Year's Eve; drawing (M)
lead_paragraph: The standard rap on New Year's Eve is that you glance backward (at the year just past) and forward (to the year ahead). That duality may not have a better musical equivalent than the Millennial Territory Orchestra, a scrappy little big band conducted by the slide trumpeter Steven Bernstein. The band's repertory stretches from prewar swing to Stevie Wonder, but its style suggests some unifying principles (like a boisterous spit-shine irreverence). Jennifer Charles, the breathy lead singer of Elysian Fields, will join the group as a special guest. And because Mr. Bernstein first formed the orchestra as a midnight staple at Tonic, they'll have a home court advantage. At 10:30 p.m., Tonic, 107 Norfolk Street, near Delancey Street, Lower East Side; (212) 358-7501, tonicnyc.com; $30, including Champagne toast. John Zorn, Guy Licata, Bill Laswell and Milford Graves perform at 8 p.m., for $30.
